.TH "INTL.LOCALE.VARIANTS" "3JS" "July 22, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Intl.Locale.variants \- Intl.Locale.prototype.variants
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]variants\f[B]\f[R] accessor property of
\f[CR]Intl.Locale\f[R] instances returns the variants associated with
this locale, as a string of dash (\f[CR]\-\f[R]) separated identifiers
in the originally specified order.
.SH DESCRIPTION
Variants are a part of the main language ID.
They select variants of a language that the (language, region, script)
triple cannot differentiate.
Usually, they represent the same language in different eras or different
orthographies.
For example, German has the \f[CR]1901\f[R] and \f[CR]1996\f[R]
orthography variants, which are written as \f[CR]de\-1901\f[R] and
\f[CR]de\-1996\f[R]; the \(lqEarly Modern English (1500\-1700)\(rq
variant is written as \f[CR]en\-emodeng\f[R].
The subtag can contain multiple identifiers separated by dashes
(\f[CR]\-\f[R]).
These identifiers are technically unordered, although in practice they
often have a semantic hierarchy\(emfor example, the Resian dialect of
Slovenian is written as \f[CR]sl\-rozaj\f[R], and the San Giorgio/Bila
dialect of Resian is written as \f[CR]sl\-rozaj\-biske\f[R].
.PP
The \f[CR]variants\f[R] property\(cqs value is set at construction time,
either through the part of the locale identifier after \f[CR]region\f[R]
or through the \f[CR]variants\f[R] option of the
\f[CR]Intl.Locale()\f[R] constructor.
The latter takes priority if they are both present; and if neither is
present, the property has value \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
.PP
The set accessor of \f[CR]variants\f[R] is \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
You cannot change this property directly.
.SH EXAMPLES
Like other locale subtags, the variants can be added to the
\f[CR]Intl.Locale\f[R] object via the locale string, or a configuration
object argument to the constructor.
.SS Adding variants via the locale string
The variants, if present, are the last parts of a valid Unicode language
identifier string, and can be added to the initial locale identifier
string that is passed into the \f[CR]Intl.Locale()\f[R] constructor.
Note that the variants are not a required part of a locale identifier.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] locale = \f[B]new\f[R] Intl.Locale(\(dqsl\-rozaj\-biske\(dq);
console.log(locale.variants); \f[I]// \(dqrozaj\-biske\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.SS Adding variants via the configuration object argument
The \f[CR]Intl.Locale()\f[R] constructor has an optional configuration
object argument.
Set the \f[CR]variants\f[R] property of the configuration object to your
desired variants, and then pass it into the constructor.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] locale = \f[B]new\f[R] Intl.Locale(\(dqsl\(dq, { variants: \(dqrozaj\-biske\(dq });
console.log(locale.variants); \f[I]// \(dqrozaj\-biske\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Intl.Locale\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
